Each learning screen decides where its own lines belong:

self.display.divider(38)
self.display.divider(112)
self.display.divider(165)
self.display.divider(205)

Those values are only a starting layout:

0–38       title and WPM
39–112     SEND and hint
113–165    user input
166–205    result or feedback
206–239    soft buttons

The important part is to place each line between existing text areas, not through them. Since screens do not all use identical coordinates, you should not blindly copy the same four positions into every file.

The screens that likely need checking are:

single_character.py
random_groups.py
random_words.py
practice.py, if you want sections there too

power - 1 li-ion cell
How I would wire it

For one-cell operation:

Li-ion cell
    │
protection / charger
    │
power switch
    │
3.3 V buck-boost
    │
    ├── Pico 3V3 pin
    ├── display 3.3 V
    └── speaker transistor supply
    Everything shares ground.
    The speaker still does not connect directly to the regulator output as an audio signal. The regulated 3.3 V powers the speaker/transistor circuit, while GP4 provides PWM to the transistor through the resistor.

3.3 V regulated
     │
   speaker
     │
 transistor
     │
    GND

GP4 ─ resistor ─ transistor base

But there are two possible power architectures
Simpler architecture
1S Li-ion → Pico VSYS
Pico 3V3 → display and speaker circuit

This uses the Pico’s onboard regulator. It is simple and probably adequate.

More controlled architecture
1S Li-ion → buck-boost 3.3 V
                 │
                 ├── Pico 3V3
                 ├── display
                 └── speaker stage
However, supplying the Pico through 3V3 bypasses its onboard regulator, so USB power interaction must be handled carefully. You should not casually connect USB while an external 3.3 V regulator is driving the same rail.

For a prototype, the safest approach is probably:

battery mode:
1S cell → buck-boost 3.3 V → unit

USB programming mode:
battery power switched off